1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:08,442
The talks for the rest of the week will centre on the Four Noble Truths, which was the first teaching the Buddha gave after his enlightenment.

2
00:00:09,784 --> 00:00:16,573
He described these as his own insights into the nature of suffering and the process by which it is eliminated.

3
00:00:17,774 --> 00:00:21,600
When he gave this teaching, he added an injunct with each truth.

4
00:00:22,961 --> 00:00:25,144
These bring the teaching alive for us.

5
00:00:26,446 --> 00:00:28,890
We can live the Four Noble Truths.

6
00:00:30,827 --> 00:00:33,673
So what are these truths the Buddha wants us to live by?

7
00:00:33,692 --> 00:00:37,698
The first is that life involves dukkha.

8
00:00:38,820 --> 00:00:42,106
The injunction here is to fully understand dukkha.

9
00:00:43,509 --> 00:00:47,395
The second truth states that desire is the cause of dukkha.

10
00:00:48,637 --> 00:00:51,121
The Buddha asks us to let go of desire.

11
00:00:52,923 --> 00:00:57,932
The third truth is the good news, that there is an end to dukkha.

12
00:00:58,942 --> 00:01:02,026
The injunction is to realize the end of dukkha.

13
00:01:03,808 --> 00:01:12,281
Finally, we have more good news, that there is a way to the end of dukkha, namely the noble eightfold path.

14
00:01:13,722 --> 00:01:16,167
The injunction is to follow this path.

15
00:01:19,210 --> 00:01:23,817
Let's start off tonight with the first noble truth, the truth of dukkha.

16
00:01:25,924 --> 00:01:30,271
For people with only a superficial interest in Buddhism, this can be off-putting.

17
00:01:31,412 --> 00:01:35,658
It's easy to deride Buddhists as pessimists because of the focus on suffering.

18
00:01:37,120 --> 00:01:41,406
Our culture more often encourages us to ignore the unsavoury aspects of life.

19
00:01:42,507 --> 00:01:44,730
We don't like to discuss death, for example.

20
00:01:46,191 --> 00:01:52,319
Just this morning, I was listening to a radio interview with four people who had lost their spouses.

21
00:01:52,537 --> 00:01:59,688
One man who had obviously had a very close relationship with his wife said his only regret was that they never discussed her death.

22
00:02:01,072 --> 00:02:04,358
They both knew she was dying but couldn't acknowledge it openly.

23
00:02:04,397 --> 00:02:11,490
He sensed her growing distant from him in her last weeks because of this gap between them.

24
00:02:13,006 --> 00:02:18,431
When asked why he didn't broach the subject, he said it was because he didn't know how.

25
00:02:18,471 --> 00:02:26,318
They had both tried so hard to be optimistic and positive, and he didn't know how to break through that pattern.

26
00:02:29,081 --> 00:02:36,068
I think this is a good illustration of our cultural difficulty around opening to death and other unwelcome aspects of life.

27
00:02:37,150 --> 00:02:38,912
We just don't know how to open.

28
00:02:40,241 --> 00:02:49,873
We build up habits of optimism and cheerfulness to try to buoy ourselves up, but then get stuck in these habits and lose touch with our deeper reality.

29
00:02:52,097 --> 00:02:59,866
His regrets around not having spoken to his wife about her impending death also shows the trap of our focus on the positive.

30
00:03:01,627 --> 00:03:07,836
It prevents the development and expression of a love which transcends our wishes for how life should be.

31
00:03:12,085 --> 00:03:20,258
It is ironic that the path to happiness starts with an understanding of unhappiness, but this was the Buddha's great insight.

32
00:03:21,580 --> 00:03:27,230
Once he fully understood the nature of suffering, he became completely free from suffering.

33
00:03:28,413 --> 00:03:37,788
He was untroubled, quiet at ease and content throughout all the vicissitudes of life, and even as he died a painful death from food poisoning.

34
00:03:39,337 --> 00:03:47,290
He was open and unsentimental about the fact that he was dying, and not a bit impressed with his cousin Ananda for weeping at the news.

35
00:03:49,373 --> 00:03:54,823
With characteristic pragmatism, he reminded Ananda that old worldly pleasures fade away.

36
00:03:54,842 --> 00:04:02,594
He was willing and able to teach right up to the moment of death, leaving his followers with the words,

37
00:04:03,064 --> 00:04:06,050
All conditioned things have the nature to decay.

38
00:04:06,090 --> 00:04:10,056
Strive diligently for your liberation.

39
00:04:13,820 --> 00:04:16,865
He described dukkha as coming in three flavours.

40
00:04:18,468 --> 00:04:20,971
Firstly, there is dukkha dukkha.

41
00:04:22,454 --> 00:04:33,149
which is what we normally recognize as suffering, illness, pain, death, redundancy, financial ruin, old age, bereavement and so on.

42
00:04:34,571 --> 00:04:39,497
Then there is Anika Dukkha, resulting from the transient nature of life.

43
00:04:40,740 --> 00:04:50,553
And finally there is Anatta Dukkha, the existential angst we can feel because we don't have any meaningful degree of control over our lives.

44
00:04:52,862 --> 00:04:56,348
Duka duka is the most difficult for us to deal with.

45
00:04:57,569 --> 00:05:03,839
We go through shock, anger, grief and so on before coming to terms with major life challenges.

46
00:05:05,562 --> 00:05:07,745
Duka duka is inescapable.

47
00:05:09,088 --> 00:05:12,653
Even if we live a charmed life, we will someday have to die.

48
00:05:12,713 --> 00:05:20,946
And if we're lucky enough to have a long life, we'll have to negotiate our way through the various humiliations of old age along the way.

49
00:05:22,005 --> 00:05:32,644
For many people, this dukkha dukkha is their only encounter with the limitations of life, and they can be really thrown off course by the death of a loved one, for example.

50
00:05:34,447 --> 00:05:40,437
The incidence of depression increases with age, and the risk of suicide is highest in the elderly.

51
00:05:43,454 --> 00:05:52,404
As a way of preparing ourselves for the inevitable, we can practice on the milder forms of dukkha relating to anicca and anatta.

52
00:05:55,028 --> 00:05:57,170
Let's look at anicca dukkha first.

53
00:05:58,372 --> 00:06:02,197
The dissatisfaction we feel because of the transitory nature of life.

54
00:06:05,281 --> 00:06:07,865
We have loads of examples of this in our daily life.

55
00:06:08,985 --> 00:06:10,507
Take a holiday for example.

56
00:06:12,023 --> 00:06:21,214
We can get quite excited at the prospect, looking through the brochures, checking out the hotels, booking time off work.

57
00:06:21,235 --> 00:06:22,576
Then we're on holiday.

58
00:06:22,617 --> 00:06:26,040
It can take a day or two to settle and relax.

59
00:06:27,283 --> 00:06:30,726
If we're lucky, we'll enjoy ourselves and appreciate our stay.

60
00:06:32,108 --> 00:06:36,834
But how quickly that final day comes round when we have to pack and go home again.

61
00:06:36,894 --> 00:06:40,680
And there's still the hotel bill to be paid.

62
00:06:42,112 --> 00:06:53,387
Sometimes we're energised and refreshed by the holiday, chatting to our colleagues and friends about what we've seen, but eventually the gloss wears off and we're back to our daily routine again.

63
00:06:53,447 --> 00:07:03,579
That's the essence of Anicca Dukkha, the dissatisfaction we feel because the good times just don't last forever.

64
00:07:05,432 --> 00:07:12,963
It can be quite subtle and we might not feel it as a major problem, just part of life, we say philosophically.

65
00:07:15,326 --> 00:07:18,831
But the Buddha's advice is not to dismiss the problem so readily.

66
00:07:19,872 --> 00:07:28,064
Take an interest in the ending and aftermath of the holiday as much as the exciting and relaxing times before and during the holiday.

67
00:07:30,086 --> 00:07:36,536
we often find ways to ignore the slight downer at the end, planning the next holiday for example.

68
00:07:39,761 --> 00:07:49,675
The problem with ignoring the endings of all our happy times is that we get addicted to activity or other forms of escapism as a means of keeping our spirits up.

69
00:07:50,557 --> 00:07:59,149
We look to the future, the next exciting thing in life, to keep our mind off the fact that something we cared for has just ended.

70
00:08:01,036 --> 00:08:12,596
If we persist in this, keeping ourselves buoyed up and cheerful at all costs, then we will have no resources to deal with the inevitable dukkha dukkha when it comes.

71
00:08:14,961 --> 00:08:18,807
I first noticed Anicca dukkha as I was reading a book.

72
00:08:19,413 --> 00:08:23,343
I was always a great reader and would never go anywhere without a book for company.

73
00:08:23,985 --> 00:08:26,855
At the hairdressers, on the bus, during coffee.

74
00:08:27,415 --> 00:08:29,281
So long as I had a book, I was happy.

75
00:08:30,204 --> 00:08:32,831
I was pretty well addicted to reading, you could say.

76
00:08:33,706 --> 00:08:41,966
And then one day, I suddenly became aware that the number of pages on the right, the unread pages, was less than the number of pages on the left.

77
00:08:43,188 --> 00:08:44,653
I felt quite depressed by this.

78
00:08:45,615 --> 00:08:49,605
From then on, I began to dread turning each page.

79
00:08:50,345 --> 00:08:54,250
When I finished the book, I felt a real downer and also a sense of shame.

80
00:08:54,270 --> 00:09:03,605
I was suddenly aware that the pleasure from reading was transitory, that it ended with the book, and therefore couldn't satisfy me at any depth.

81
00:09:05,448 --> 00:09:09,495
I was ashamed of having devoted so much of my life to this false god.

82
00:09:10,677 --> 00:09:14,884
This was quite a shock for me, and it was years before I would read a book again.

83
00:09:16,972 --> 00:09:20,158
If we look closely, we see everything is in transit.

84
00:09:21,139 --> 00:09:25,547
It arises, shows itself for a moment before passing away again.

85
00:09:25,567 --> 00:09:29,072
Take any meal, lunch for example.

86
00:09:30,234 --> 00:09:32,177
It can be hard work getting this started.

87
00:09:32,817 --> 00:09:35,142
We may have to do some shopping and then the cooking.

88
00:09:36,222 --> 00:09:39,148
At least we're buoyed up through this by the prospect of lunch.

89
00:09:39,749 --> 00:09:41,731
Then comes the nice bit, eating.

90
00:09:42,741 --> 00:09:47,929
And if there are others with us, this can be a lovely part of the day, a time to relax and chat.

91
00:09:48,711 --> 00:09:50,153
But how quickly it ends!

92
00:09:50,874 --> 00:09:52,355
And there's still the washing up to be done.

93
00:09:55,421 --> 00:10:05,895
Although we prefer to fudge around endings, distracting ourselves with whatever is next on the horizon, the wiser approach is to use this opportunity to get to know dukkha.

94
00:10:07,639 --> 00:10:10,403
So how do you experience the ending of lunch?

95
00:10:11,075 --> 00:10:15,441
See how you feel before lunch and how eager you are for the first bite.

96
00:10:16,783 --> 00:10:19,086
Does your mood lift as your stomach fills?

97
00:10:20,249 --> 00:10:21,389
And then the ending.

98
00:10:21,409 --> 00:10:26,697
Are you still so enthusiastic when the plate shows those last messy smears of food?

99
00:10:28,019 --> 00:10:30,423
Or do you just feel you have to get the job done?

100
00:10:31,905 --> 00:10:36,913
Can you rest with whatever emotions might surface as you swallow the last bite?

101
00:10:39,745 --> 00:10:48,193
I remember on the final day of a retreat at Gaia House how much I was looking forward to the evening bowl of soup and it was delicious.

102
00:10:49,335 --> 00:10:53,960
But as the bowl emptied my world actually seemed to fall apart.

103
00:10:54,841 --> 00:10:56,763
I wanted that soup to last forever.

104
00:10:56,822 --> 00:11:01,148
It seemed to hold all the goodness of life for me.

105
00:11:01,168 --> 00:11:03,389
How could I let it go?

106
00:11:04,484 --> 00:11:06,166
What would there be left in the world?

107
00:11:07,086 --> 00:11:09,369
A big gap yawned open inside me.

108
00:11:09,990 --> 00:11:13,432
For a moment I was very frightened, and then grief surfaced.

109
00:11:14,354 --> 00:11:19,479
The grief was actually a relief, and I began to acknowledge other losses in life.

110
00:11:21,642 --> 00:11:31,892
This was a good illustration of anicca dukkha for me, and how opening to it mindfully helps us work with the inescapable dukkha of life and death.

111
00:11:34,437 --> 00:11:38,265
Each breath and footstep teaches us about Anicca.

112
00:11:39,467 --> 00:11:42,956
Which do you prefer, the in-breath or the out-breath?

113
00:11:44,399 --> 00:11:45,982
Do you like to hold your breath?

114
00:11:47,009 --> 00:11:53,879
When I am anxious, I tend to gasp at the start of the in-breath and my confidence grows as I inhale.

115
00:11:53,938 --> 00:11:57,845
But then comes the moment when I have to let it all go again.

116
00:11:57,904 --> 00:12:06,337
I do my best to ignore the out-breath as I look forward to that moment when I can snatch another ray of hope that comes with the in-breath.

117
00:12:07,360 --> 00:12:08,881
This is Anicca Dukkha.

118
00:12:10,128 --> 00:12:17,807
Anxiety is prompting me to hold on to what I enjoy, the sense of possibility and hope that comes with each in-breath.

119
00:12:19,009 --> 00:12:22,076
But anxiety will not let me relax with the out-breath.

120
00:12:22,839 --> 00:12:23,721
Let go of hope?

121
00:12:24,182 --> 00:12:24,964
No way!

122
00:12:31,306 --> 00:12:41,458
Nowadays when anxiety strikes I can usually let myself feel the fear of letting go and find a thin thread of trust that pulls me through.

123
00:12:41,519 --> 00:12:50,691
This comes from moments during previous out breaths when I saw that letting go of hope does not mean the end of all hope.

124
00:12:52,293 --> 00:12:58,782
It simply releases hope to do its proper job of reassuring us deep down that all is well.

125
00:13:00,162 --> 00:13:09,634
In the words of Julian of Norwich, All shall be well, and all shall be well, and all manner of things shall be well.

126
00:13:12,099 --> 00:13:13,179
What about the footstep?

127
00:13:14,361 --> 00:13:17,787
Do you prefer the lifting, the moving or the placing?

128
00:13:19,369 --> 00:13:21,792
At first I could only sense the lifting.

129
00:13:22,432 --> 00:13:23,173
It thrilled me.

130
00:13:24,275 --> 00:13:26,658
I had a sense of soaring with the angels.

131
00:13:27,567 --> 00:13:34,255
I didn't notice anything about the rest of the step, so intent was I in looking forward to the next time I could lift my foot.

132
00:13:35,998 --> 00:13:39,682
As time went on, I also became fascinated by the moving.

133
00:13:42,505 --> 00:13:45,649
This was more wonderment than the soaring of angels.

134
00:13:47,773 --> 00:13:48,794
Could I feel anything?

135
00:13:51,337 --> 00:13:52,318
What was I feeling?

136
00:13:53,581 --> 00:13:55,363
How did I know my foot was moving?

137
00:13:56,962 --> 00:14:00,452
But the ending of the footstep was another matter entirely.

138
00:14:00,472 --> 00:14:07,091
I felt uncertain, unsteady as the foot came downwards, searching for the floor.

139
00:14:08,860 --> 00:14:14,493
and when the toe touched down, the lightness of that touch seemed totally unsatisfactory.

140
00:14:14,533 --> 00:14:27,662
Even with my full weight on the floor, I felt unhappy under that lovely moment of the heel rising, the foot peeling off the floor, when all my woes would end for another few moments.

141
00:14:31,894 --> 00:14:41,486
What all this shows me is how addicted I am to new beginnings and how I prefer to ignore the uncertainty that comes with endings.

142
00:14:43,089 --> 00:14:45,773
I can see this at other levels of life.

143
00:14:46,854 --> 00:14:55,184
I love springtime but find it hard to appreciate the lovely colours of the fall because they represent the end of the summer.

144
00:14:56,701 --> 00:14:57,942
I'm a morning person.

145
00:14:59,124 --> 00:15:04,150
I love the purity of dawn, whereas I easily get agitated in the evenings.

146
00:15:05,893 --> 00:15:12,701
I can be good at getting projects going, exploring new territory, but find it hard to see them through to the end.

147
00:15:15,405 --> 00:15:23,316
I used to do quite a lot of hill walking, and to my surprise one day, I found I preferred the uphill climb to the downhill stroll.

148
00:15:24,528 --> 00:15:29,481
Going upwards, I had a sense of hope, a promise of some reward to come.

149
00:15:31,145 --> 00:15:35,017
Coming down, on the other hand, was literally that, a come down.

150
00:15:35,037 --> 00:15:37,102
There was nothing to anticipate.

151
00:15:41,639 --> 00:15:44,962
The years of meditation practice have smoothed me out a bit.

152
00:15:45,904 --> 00:15:51,652
Just last year I noticed to my surprise that I was enjoying the ending of the footstep.

153
00:15:52,614 --> 00:15:57,379
It felt satisfying to put my foot down on the floor and let it take all my weight.

154
00:15:58,642 --> 00:16:00,484
A little bit of progress at last.

155
00:16:03,628 --> 00:16:10,076
The study of Anicca has also shown me how much delusion I can have about new beginnings.

156
00:16:11,373 --> 00:16:24,451
The sense of anticipation, hope and expectancy can rocket me into the new venture, all excited and thrilled and knowing this is going to be wonderful and that I'll be well able for the challenge.

157
00:16:26,374 --> 00:16:33,043
But when I eventually hit the ground, I'm looking around wondering how I got here and what I'm supposed to be doing.

158
00:16:34,761 --> 00:16:51,726
Nowadays, I'm better at noticing all those exciting feelings of expectancy and anticipation and steady myself on the launch pad, wait a bit to try to get some bearings before take-off.

159
00:16:51,746 --> 00:16:55,653
I've noticed that there can be a lot of fear around new beginnings.

160
00:16:56,714 --> 00:16:59,317
Each one is a venture into the unknown.

161
00:17:00,783 --> 00:17:11,180
And I sense how my eagerness to start is a reaction to that fear, wanting to get rid of that scary unknown by filling it with activity.

162
00:17:17,128 --> 00:17:20,934
Endings too can frighten us with a sense of the unknown.

163
00:17:22,213 --> 00:17:26,298
Take my life and death bowl of soup after my retreat, for example.

164
00:17:27,239 --> 00:17:28,940
That ending scared me so.

165
00:17:30,060 --> 00:17:32,202
Again, it was fear of the unknown.

166
00:17:32,242 --> 00:17:34,065
The soup was known.

167
00:17:35,145 --> 00:17:36,307
How could it just end?

168
00:17:37,528 --> 00:17:41,932
Can what we know actually disappear, become unknown?

169
00:17:46,435 --> 00:17:51,681
Working with the unknown is such a big part of our meditation practice.

170
00:17:54,309 --> 00:18:03,647
As we are drawn into the present moment we lose touch with the certainties sewn into our stories and sense the shifting sands beneath.

171
00:18:04,849 --> 00:18:06,132
What do we really know?

172
00:18:06,211 --> 00:18:16,571
Just sensations and feelings really and these are shifting and changing so fast it's hard to claim any real knowledge of them.

173
00:18:17,969 --> 00:18:26,798
While my body contacts the sensations, my mind is drawn towards a mental image I am making in my efforts to make sense of the experience.

174
00:18:28,520 --> 00:18:32,226
I imagine a big space in which the sensations are manifesting.

175
00:18:33,606 --> 00:18:35,328
It puzzles me, this space.

176
00:18:37,571 --> 00:18:41,817
Sensations seem to twinkle like stars in its vast emptiness.

177
00:18:44,902 --> 00:18:52,292
Now, what can we say about that emptiness, that space where sensations appear and into which they disappear?

178
00:18:53,734 --> 00:18:55,917
Not a lot, nothing perhaps.

179
00:18:57,119 --> 00:19:02,627
It can still frighten me to sense myself so close to such a vast unknown.

180
00:19:05,070 --> 00:19:07,855
Fear projects all kinds of monsters into it.

181
00:19:09,573 --> 00:19:18,766
But despite my best efforts at suspicion, fear and even panic, all I can say really is it has never lived up to my expectations.

182
00:19:19,446 --> 00:19:22,310
It has never, ever threatened me in any way.

183
00:19:23,952 --> 00:19:30,281
I am more and more willing to trust that it is truly and deeply non-harming.

184
00:19:33,484 --> 00:19:39,290
In ordinary life, the unknown appears in our minds when we think about the future, the next moment.

185
00:19:40,353 --> 00:19:42,234
It's behind the door before we open it.

186
00:19:43,695 --> 00:19:45,939
Thoughts also connect us with the unknown.

187
00:19:46,980 --> 00:19:48,721
I think of a friend and wish them well.

188
00:19:49,702 --> 00:19:50,923
But where are they right now?

189
00:19:50,943 --> 00:19:56,871
I might have a nice image of them sitting in a garden, but ultimately I have to admit I don't know.

190
00:19:56,911 --> 00:19:58,573
How are they feeling?

191
00:19:58,972 --> 00:19:59,913
I haven't a clue.

192
00:20:01,278 --> 00:20:11,512
The amount we don't know far outweighs what we do know, where and how our friends and family are, what's going to happen tomorrow, next year, in 20 years.

193
00:20:12,394 --> 00:20:15,519
So we have to get used to the unknown if we're going to have any peace.

194
00:20:16,701 --> 00:20:21,327
Anicca, with its beginnings and endings, provides the perfect opportunity.

195
00:20:24,666 --> 00:20:32,253
I've been describing the difficulties we experience due to anicca, but the truth of anicca can also be experienced as joyous.

196
00:20:33,174 --> 00:20:37,518
The flow of sensations as the foot peels off the floor can be exhilarating.

197
00:20:38,338 --> 00:20:41,741
The slight sways of the body as we walk can be fascinating.

198
00:20:42,742 --> 00:20:45,144
The smooth ripple of breath can be relaxing.

199
00:20:46,747 --> 00:20:52,951
We can watch and wonder as sensations and feelings stream through consciousness like water through a sieve.

200
00:20:54,214 --> 00:20:57,258
We can feel truly alive in the shifting flux.

201
00:20:59,140 --> 00:21:14,355
And when I worked through my latest bout of fear and anxiety to make peace with the unknown, then it is delightful to let myself relax and let the breath come and go of its own accord, let emotions emerge and develop and fade away.

202
00:21:14,395 --> 00:21:17,038
The transience is thrilling.

203
00:21:18,380 --> 00:21:21,403
It's perfectly okay not to know what will happen next.

204
00:21:22,852 --> 00:21:29,579
Intertwined with Anicca is the experience of Anatta, usually translated as not-self.

205
00:21:31,082 --> 00:21:33,565
This is a difficult truth to come to terms with.

206
00:21:34,826 --> 00:21:48,942
Our minds are deeply conditioned to think in terms of me and you and him and her and so on, and we find this shift in perspective to not-me, not-I, not-self quite perplexing.

207
00:21:50,542 --> 00:22:00,672
The negativity that can come with being perplexed, frustration, confusion, anxiety, etc., is one manifestation of anatta dukkha.

208
00:22:02,930 --> 00:22:08,178
To my mind, the kernel of fear that forms anicca dukkha is fear of the unknown.

209
00:22:09,619 --> 00:22:18,113
By comparison, I think much of the dukkha associated with anatta revolves around fear of not understanding.

210
00:22:18,173 --> 00:22:30,152
That can make us feel like small children at school, feeling stupid and ashamed because we don't understand our lessons, frightened the teacher and the other kids will jeer at us.

211
00:22:31,246 --> 00:22:38,739
So look out for these kinds of emotions when you're exploring Anatta, even now as you listen to the talk, for example.

212
00:22:40,241 --> 00:22:49,878
If they surface, see can you model the kind of teacher kids love, patient, encouraging, prepared to stop the lessons to have some fun.

213
00:22:51,157 --> 00:23:02,952
and especially to notice and resist any tendency to put yourself down, hate yourself because of how slowly this teaching is sinking in, or judge yourself as stupid and so on.

214
00:23:04,214 --> 00:23:14,468
If that happens, definitely time to stop the Anatta lesson and focus instead on those jeering kids or teachers that have popped up in your imagination to taunt you.

215
00:23:16,590 --> 00:23:18,313
Back to the Anatta lesson now.

216
00:23:19,441 --> 00:23:21,963
What do we mean when we say, I am?

217
00:23:21,983 --> 00:23:25,287
It easily trots off our lips.

218
00:23:26,208 --> 00:23:26,868
I am happy.

219
00:23:26,888 --> 00:23:28,730
I am cold.

220
00:23:28,750 --> 00:23:30,593
I am an engineer.

221
00:23:30,613 --> 00:23:32,775
I am meditating.

222
00:23:34,517 --> 00:23:43,406
A step closer to the truth of Anatta would be to say, there is a being who is happy, cold, etc.

223
00:23:44,769 --> 00:23:49,717
and by some magic this being's experience and life story are known.

224
00:23:51,459 --> 00:23:58,769
It's so tempting to add, by me, to say, this being's experience and life story are known by me.

225
00:23:58,828 --> 00:24:03,894
Let's try to bring this closer to the truth of anatta.

226
00:24:06,199 --> 00:24:11,065
There is a concept of me, myself, I, who knows this being.

227
00:24:12,799 --> 00:24:17,826
Our concepts are a mental construction derived from our perceptions of the world.

228
00:24:19,189 --> 00:24:23,994
That's essentially what the self is, according to the Buddha, a mental construction.

229
00:24:26,878 --> 00:24:31,384
Perceptions are the mind's attempts to make sense of all the data it receives.

230
00:24:32,646 --> 00:24:36,853
We see a certain pattern of yellow colours and perceive a buttercup.

231
00:24:38,054 --> 00:24:41,659
We hear a jangling sound and perceive a doorbell.

232
00:24:42,752 --> 00:24:46,417
One teacher likens perception to a mental filing cabinet.

233
00:24:47,359 --> 00:24:51,445
Each bit of sensory information is put into its correct file.

234
00:24:51,486 --> 00:24:59,958
The ability to perceive helps us simplify the vast amount of data bombarding our senses each moment.

235
00:25:01,359 --> 00:25:05,746
If we didn't have our filing cabinet, the paper would be strewn all over the room.

236
00:25:06,988 --> 00:25:08,369
It would be total confusion.

237
00:25:09,271 --> 00:25:10,313
We couldn't function.

238
00:25:11,827 --> 00:25:18,979
Babies haven't yet learned to categorise experience in this way, and so have endless fun exploring their little world.

239
00:25:20,421 --> 00:25:21,563
Everything is new.

240
00:25:21,603 --> 00:25:35,202
As adults, we learn to ignore much of our sense input, as it's so quickly stowed away into its correct file, and we gladly believe that much of it can be labelled as unimportant.

241
00:25:37,646 --> 00:25:39,648
The ability to perceive is wonderful.

242
00:25:40,289 --> 00:25:44,074
We couldn't negotiate our way through the world without this simplification.

243
00:25:45,234 --> 00:25:52,163
But it's important to remember that it's a mental classification, a form of data processing that we do.

244
00:25:53,744 --> 00:25:59,151
Our perceptions are not inherent to the world but a construction in our minds.

245
00:26:02,094 --> 00:26:03,756
Our perceptions can be wrong

246
00:26:04,833 --> 00:26:11,099
We've probably all had the experience of mistaking a stranger for a friend because of some trick of the light.

247
00:26:12,500 --> 00:26:15,144
For a brief moment we see our friend.

248
00:26:16,105 --> 00:26:17,727
We may even stop to say hello.

249
00:26:17,767 --> 00:26:22,291
Then the scene changes and a stranger's face comes into view.

250
00:26:22,311 --> 00:26:25,955
The incoming data went into the wrong file.

251
00:26:25,996 --> 00:26:28,057
We can get quite a shock.

252
00:26:29,640 --> 00:26:31,481
Sometimes the opposite happens.

253
00:26:32,946 --> 00:26:41,701
Recently I was waiting at a station when my eyes were for some reason attracted towards a strange woman's face and I found myself staring at her.

254
00:26:42,561 --> 00:26:43,743
She stared back.

255
00:26:44,724 --> 00:26:47,048
It took a second to recognise a friend.

256
00:26:47,910 --> 00:26:49,313
We both started giggling.

257
00:26:50,094 --> 00:26:57,164
We hadn't been expecting to see one another there and the raw data got misclassified as the perception stranger.

258
00:27:00,470 --> 00:27:07,198
I had a very striking example of this one time on retreat here at Satipanya when I came into the meditation room.

259
00:27:08,719 --> 00:27:18,150
It was the original room before the extension and some of you may remember that Bhante kept the prayer plant on its tall table just beside the side door.

260
00:27:19,372 --> 00:27:25,137
The pair are now in the dining room so look out for this misperception if you stray into the dining room at night.

261
00:27:26,880 --> 00:27:29,363
The table is draped with a red cloth.

262
00:27:31,604 --> 00:27:37,675
There was no one in the shrine room and I crossed over in the semi-darkness and switched on the light by the shrine.

263
00:27:37,695 --> 00:27:50,962
As I turned back, eyes downcast, I glimpsed the red cloth brushing the floor and in an instant my mind built up a life-size image of Bhante standing beside the door.

264
00:27:50,942 --> 00:28:04,403
In my mind, I saw Bhante, gave a startled jump as I hadn't heard him come in, felt embarrassed at my jumpiness and was about to apologise before I realised I was about to address a pot plant.

265
00:28:08,068 --> 00:28:11,734
Our perceptions are our best attempt to make sense of the world.

266
00:28:12,696 --> 00:28:15,461
They're influenced by our memories and expectations.

267
00:28:16,422 --> 00:28:17,523
They can be wrong.

268
00:28:19,208 --> 00:28:21,431
So it is with the perception of self.

269
00:28:22,571 --> 00:28:23,373
It can be wrong.

270
00:28:25,375 --> 00:28:27,617
At times it's an appropriate perception.

271
00:28:28,157 --> 00:28:29,839
It helps make sense of the world.

272
00:28:31,422 --> 00:28:33,744
This is true in much of our daily lives.

273
00:28:35,547 --> 00:28:42,054
This being, I call me, is staying in the library so needs to get herself there at times.

274
00:28:43,276 --> 00:28:48,961
If I didn't have an ability to perceive myself as different to others who knows where I would end up.

275
00:28:51,862 --> 00:28:55,786
But this perception is not the ultimate truth, according to the Buddha.

276
00:28:57,667 --> 00:29:01,191
There are times where a perception of not-self is more helpful.

277
00:29:02,913 --> 00:29:07,478
Take those times when we are avidly watching the flow of sensations and feelings.

278
00:29:08,878 --> 00:29:10,941
Then things start to feel sticky.

279
00:29:12,001 --> 00:29:15,244
We tighten around pleasant feelings, trying to hold on to them.

280
00:29:16,287 --> 00:29:17,768
The flow gets choked up.

281
00:29:19,012 --> 00:29:24,858
If we can relax and let go, sensations and feelings flow more easily again.

282
00:29:26,799 --> 00:29:36,410
If you look carefully, you will also notice that a sense of self arises when things get sticky and is released when sensations are flowing.

283
00:29:36,450 --> 00:29:46,219
This is a teaching on the truth of anatta, that the self arises depending on conditions.

284
00:29:50,451 --> 00:29:57,479
The particular condition needed to generate a sense of self is a pleasant or unpleasant feeling we cling to.

285
00:29:57,539 --> 00:30:04,666
We try to hold, amplify and prolong the pleasant, we try to get rid of the unpleasant.

286
00:30:06,828 --> 00:30:14,096
If you look closely, the perception of self is associated with the pleasant feeling of control.

287
00:30:15,477 --> 00:30:17,179
We love to feel in control.

288
00:30:17,239 --> 00:30:20,001
It means we can do what we want.

289
00:30:20,682 --> 00:30:21,383
We're the boss.

290
00:30:22,785 --> 00:30:28,130
We especially want to feel in control of ourselves, our bodies, emotions, thoughts.

291
00:30:29,632 --> 00:30:31,953
We want to be in good humour when we're on holiday.

292
00:30:32,013 --> 00:30:35,518
We want to think positive when we're going for interview.

293
00:30:36,479 --> 00:30:39,662
We want our bodies to be able to move and function normally.

294
00:30:40,856 --> 00:30:45,362
When we can't meet these expectations, we can feel quite threatened.

295
00:30:46,884 --> 00:30:54,592
Our language actually contains a hint of Anatta when we describe these times as, I'm not myself today.

296
00:30:54,612 --> 00:30:57,275
She wasn't like herself at all.

297
00:30:58,757 --> 00:31:00,719
He was beside himself with rage.

298
00:31:04,182 --> 00:31:06,105
What's actually happening here?

299
00:31:07,688 --> 00:31:20,904
When we look closely we see that when things are going well for us there is a pleasant feeling which we perceive as me and believe to be the control centre for our body, mind and life.

300
00:31:23,028 --> 00:31:30,017
When things go badly unpleasant feelings are generated which we push away thinking this isn't me.

301
00:31:31,279 --> 00:31:43,480
We're frightened by the fact that things are going against our wishes and especially when we notice the unpleasant sensations and associated feelings are also manifesting in our bodies.

302
00:31:45,022 --> 00:31:47,548
Where is our precious control centre now?

303
00:31:47,587 --> 00:31:56,021
If you look carefully you will find it's boxed into the opposition to the way things are.

304
00:31:57,622 --> 00:32:05,314
Even though the whole world can look black and scary, there is still a tiny, pleasant feeling of holding onto control.

305
00:32:05,374 --> 00:32:14,749
So long as I can say no to what I don't want, I can persuade myself I'm still in control.

306
00:32:19,215 --> 00:32:23,663
In general, the feeling of self accompanies any sense of effort.

307
00:32:24,892 --> 00:32:31,087
Any time you feel relatively peaceful in meditation, see whether there is a strong sense of self.

308
00:32:33,133 --> 00:32:36,240
Compare that to the times you feel yourself struggling.

309
00:32:38,366 --> 00:32:41,314
The hindrances come with a strong sense of self.

310
00:32:43,268 --> 00:32:51,717
When I'm struggling with physical pain, I feel my body straining away from the painful area, as if it's trying to divide itself in two.

311
00:32:52,458 --> 00:33:00,046
The painful part, sensed as not me, and the part which pulls away, sensed as me.

312
00:33:01,446 --> 00:33:05,791
As I make peace with the pain, that sense of division subsides.

313
00:33:06,893 --> 00:33:12,499
Thus, physical pain provides one way for us to explore the truth of anatta.

314
00:33:15,212 --> 00:33:17,477
All this can be very bewildering.

315
00:33:18,219 --> 00:33:18,779
Am I here?

316
00:33:19,300 --> 00:33:19,961
Am I not here?

317
00:33:20,864 --> 00:33:21,625
Do I exist?

318
00:33:22,647 --> 00:33:24,211
It can be quite frightening.

319
00:33:25,633 --> 00:33:31,444
Our sense of self is very precious and we can feel threatened by thoughts of not-self.

320
00:33:32,847 --> 00:33:35,112
We imagine we will be annihilated.

321
00:33:37,690 --> 00:33:42,115
The Buddha refused to answer questions of the type, Do I exist?

322
00:33:42,776 --> 00:33:43,676
Do I not exist?

323
00:33:44,436 --> 00:33:45,838
Will I exist after death?

324
00:33:47,500 --> 00:33:53,287
Patiently he repeated his insight that the sense of self emerges to fulfil our desires.

325
00:33:55,549 --> 00:34:06,701
I think of the sense of self as a psychophysical mechanism that energises and sculpts my mind and body to help me get what I want, get rid of what I don't want.

326
00:34:08,318 --> 00:34:17,710
But when we are resting, when there isn't any enticing food to be found or any threats to cope with, we don't need central coordination.

327
00:34:19,072 --> 00:34:23,619
All the cells and organs work away themselves, just as they do in sleep.

328
00:34:25,922 --> 00:34:31,710
Unless we experience desire or aversion, no sense of self is formed.

329
00:34:33,309 --> 00:34:38,257
At these times, we often have no interest in the question, do I exist?

330
00:34:39,280 --> 00:34:40,300
It seems irrelevant.

331
00:34:41,943 --> 00:34:48,855
Then something disturbs our peaceful flow, and suddenly we're all hyped up, very sure of our existence.

332
00:34:52,581 --> 00:35:04,298
One reason why we don't easily make peace with Anatta is because we don't notice the absence of our sense of self during those peaceful times when there are no strong desires driving us.

333
00:35:05,981 --> 00:35:12,911
So we don't take those chances to explore and learn to appreciate the experience and perception not-self.

334
00:35:14,755 --> 00:35:18,099
Why don't we notice the experience of not-self?

335
00:35:19,682 --> 00:35:34,144
Although the thought of anatta is perplexing and we find it hard to imagine the possibility of existing without a sense of self, ironically the experience of anatta is quite mundane and doesn't attract our attention.

336
00:35:35,786 --> 00:35:39,974
The absence of self is not a particularly interesting experience.

337
00:35:43,980 --> 00:35:45,521
Our world doesn't fall apart.

338
00:35:46,362 --> 00:35:48,947
Our bodies and minds function just fine.

339
00:35:50,141 --> 00:35:56,650
One teacher says that the mind state of not-self is far more prevalent than the mind state of self.

340
00:35:57,692 --> 00:36:02,759
It's just that it's so unobtrusive, so ordinary, that we don't notice it.

341
00:36:07,324 --> 00:36:09,648
I find it comforting to reflect on that.

342
00:36:11,391 --> 00:36:16,538
It helps to alleviate the fear we often feel during the investigation of anatta.

343
00:36:20,398 --> 00:36:24,864
We can also investigate anatta as it shows up in our relationship with others.

344
00:36:26,586 --> 00:36:31,112
Normally we locate ourselves within our bodies and other people outside.

345
00:36:32,213 --> 00:36:38,001
But these perceptions can dissolve when we take another into our hearts in the practice of metta.

346
00:36:39,443 --> 00:36:44,269
Again, we don't usually notice this as the experience does not trouble us.

347
00:36:45,590 --> 00:36:47,554
Only trouble calls attention.

348
00:36:48,715 --> 00:36:53,730
But it can be interesting to explore this when you feel a friendship.

349
00:36:53,750 --> 00:36:57,561
Is there a clear sense of separation between you and the other?

350
00:37:00,746 --> 00:37:06,875
By contrast, the boundary between self and other gets amplified by enmity and hatred.

351
00:37:07,896 --> 00:37:13,103
When these surface, my face will often be tightening, my jaws locked.

352
00:37:14,065 --> 00:37:18,371
A strong sense of me fuels the tension, clenches my jaws.

353
00:37:19,572 --> 00:37:22,856
A mental image of the other person is projected around my head.

354
00:37:24,574 --> 00:37:33,748
As I let go of angry thoughts, their image blurs and I'm left with a vague but threatening sense of otherness beyond the borders of my body.

355
00:37:35,311 --> 00:37:44,965
The world seems to be divided into me, barricaded into my jaws and face, fiercely opposed to the other occupying the space around.

356
00:37:47,048 --> 00:37:52,657
Nowadays, I use the note, not me, to describe that sense of otherness.

357
00:37:54,443 --> 00:37:58,306
This stills my mind and increases curiosity.

358
00:37:59,789 --> 00:38:01,710
What is this entity I'm battling with?

359
00:38:03,592 --> 00:38:08,356
My mind pushes against the boundary, demanding to know what is out there.

360
00:38:10,239 --> 00:38:15,945
But nothing clarifies and my attention reverts to my body, the breath rising and falling.

361
00:38:17,766 --> 00:38:23,572
In time my face and jaws relax and the boundary between me and not me blurs.

362
00:38:24,717 --> 00:38:31,813
The space around me, once so threatening, seeps inwards, dissolving the sense of enmity.

363
00:38:33,617 --> 00:38:38,971
The image of the other person re-emerges and I begin to see the situation from their point of view.

364
00:38:40,173 --> 00:38:42,438
A sense of understanding grows.

365
00:38:45,878 --> 00:38:52,356
Exploring our relationship with others in this way helps us to come to terms with the truth of anatta.

366
00:38:53,559 --> 00:39:01,541
Perceptions of self and not-self emerge and dissolve in line with feelings of enmity and friendship.

367
00:39:04,170 --> 00:39:13,023
Whenever we start thinking about anatta, we will often be stimulating a sense of self, as the desire to know and understand the truth is operating.

368
00:39:14,164 --> 00:39:19,891
Ironically, this desire leads to a sense of self who needs to understand this truth.

369
00:39:21,393 --> 00:39:27,963
So it's quite a challenge to combine reflection on the teaching with experiential investigation.

370
00:39:29,244 --> 00:39:30,887
We need patience.

371
00:39:31,929 --> 00:39:37,862
We can also bring those emotional reactions into the field of investigation whenever they are stimulated.

372
00:39:39,626 --> 00:39:43,675
We might sense anatta in our lack of control over those emotions.

373
00:39:45,498 --> 00:39:52,032
Beware also of judging the sense of self as somehow inferior to the sense of not-self.

374
00:39:53,311 --> 00:40:04,045
Time and again the Buddha asks us to look after ourselves wisely, to treasure our human life with its opportunity to free ourselves from suffering.

375
00:40:06,248 --> 00:40:12,838
There are many wise desires we should fulfil in order to look after ourselves and practice meditation.

376
00:40:14,202 --> 00:40:20,916
The desire to learn the Dharma would be one, and then the multitude of desires involved in putting this into practice.

377
00:40:21,556 --> 00:40:32,380
For example, the desire to come on retreat, the desire to get the bus in order to come on retreat, the desire to get out of bed in order to get the bus, etc., etc.

378
00:40:33,710 --> 00:40:42,003
Many of these desires will need some effort to fulfil and a sense of self is conjured up to channel our energies into that effort.

379
00:40:43,005 --> 00:40:43,867
That's fine.

380
00:40:43,907 --> 00:40:48,293
That's the way the human organism accomplishes things.

381
00:40:51,097 --> 00:40:53,963
So a sense of self is nothing to be ashamed of.

382
00:40:55,327 --> 00:41:06,023
Ajahn Thanissaro, in his very helpful book on Anatta entitled, Selves and Not-Self, says that sometimes the perception of self is the wiser one.

383
00:41:06,985 --> 00:41:10,090
Sometimes the perception of not-self is the wiser one.

384
00:41:12,775 --> 00:41:21,148
He adds that as our practice deepens, we get better at discerning which perception is more appropriate for each situation.

385
00:41:24,367 --> 00:41:30,376
To marshal ourselves for actions we deem as worthy, the sense of self should be encouraged and nourished.

386
00:41:31,557 --> 00:41:37,565
We can search for any good feelings associated with thoughts like I can, I will, etc.

387
00:41:38,246 --> 00:41:45,297
and take delight in these as a little treasure trove to help us enjoy work and get us through any challenges.

388
00:41:46,373 --> 00:41:56,086
When we've accomplished our task or feel the need for a rest along the way, we can sit back and invite any dukkha stirred up by the activity to manifest.

389
00:41:57,668 --> 00:42:14,052
Sometimes as the struggle with dukkha wanes, we can let the perception of not me, not mine sink in to remind us that we don't always have to be acting and accomplishing, that the world can survive quite well without us.

390
00:42:14,960 --> 00:42:20,230
that even we ourselves can survive quite well without anyone at the helm.

391
00:42:24,438 --> 00:42:33,797
I want to finish off tonight by recapping on the first noble truth, that life involves dukkha.

392
00:42:33,817 --> 00:42:37,103
The Buddha asks us to fully understand dukkha.

393
00:42:38,617 --> 00:42:47,346
we can explore it in three forms, dukkha-dukkha, which involves the major suffering of our lives and which we cannot escape.

394
00:42:48,907 --> 00:42:53,291
To prepare ourselves for this, we can study dukkha's milder forms.

395
00:42:54,211 --> 00:43:01,818
Anicca-dukkha manifests especially at beginnings and endings and is even contained within the minutiae.

396
00:43:02,639 --> 00:43:08,625
Every breath, footstep and meal present us with a lesson on transience.

397
00:43:10,175 --> 00:43:24,184
Anata dukkha shows up at the limits to our control, at the boundary of me and other, and even within ourselves, as we struggle with sensations and feelings we would prefer not to own.

398
00:43:27,099 --> 00:43:33,686
The exploration of dukkha involves finding our way through the hindrances that block our view of truth.

399
00:43:35,188 --> 00:43:42,496
As we make our peace with each hindrance, we also come to terms with the limits to our knowledge and understanding.

400
00:43:44,039 --> 00:43:52,568
We feel more at ease in a world which is continually slipping through our fingers, beyond our tiny radius of control.

401
00:43:56,547 --> 00:44:05,240
May we and all beings come to understand Dukkha and thereby be liberated from all suffering.

